@node New
@title "New features in this release of The Maestrix"
@{b}New features!@{ub}

New features in version 1.2 release of The Maestrix:

@{i}This is just a simple update to The Maestrix which includes following additions in the latest version.@{ui}

@{b}¤@{ub} Re-worked buffering routines.

I have slightly optimised the buffering routines to work in a cleaner fashion so the code runs more fluently.

@{b}¤@{ub} Version 39 API support.

Some programs, although they don't use the features, try to open up a V39 of the API. So I have bumped up the reported version number and added in the V39 API support routines. Note that this is just for compatibility only, because the actual functionality of the routines is missing, as they will just return back.
@endnode

@node Install
@title "How to install The Maestrix"
@{b}Installing The Maestrix@{ub}

So you want to have this on your system right now? By opening the "Install The Maestrix" icon, it will run a script to copy files to your system. There are two main files to install, the program file and the guide file. You will be asked where you would like to install the files. As it is a commodity it will first choose WBStartup but you can put it where you like, the same goes for the guide fles which by default will go to HELP:English.
@endnode

@node Instruct
@title "Instructions on using The Maestrix"
@{b}Instructions@{ub}

There is not much you need to do to get it running, just running it basically, but if you want to configure it for AHI you can do so in the icon tooltypes, as explained below. As well as another tooltype it looks out for. All the tooltypes are not case sensitive.

@{b}AUTOQUIT@{ub}
This tells The Maestrix what to do when another copy is run, either ignore it or auto-quit. Set to YES or NO.
In any case that The Maestrix is told to quit, it will check the library and alert you if it is still open.

@{b}AHIUNIT@{ub}
This sets the AHI UNIT that will be used. This can be set to NONE, DEFAULT, or a number between 0 and 255. Anything else and you will encounter an error, go on, try it out.

@{b}Setting up OctaMED SoundStudio@{ub}

As mentioned earlier, one of the major uses of The Maestrix and what it was mainly tested on, is SoundStudio. Here I detail how to set it up for use on AmigaOS4, those that don't have a sound card supported directly or a newer based classic system with a PCI sound card.

In Song menu, select "Set Options..." item, and pick "1-64 Ch Mixing". Exit.
In Settings menu, select "Mixing Setttings" item, and pick "MaestroPro 16-bit". Exit.
In Settings menu again , select Miscellaneous... item, now check on "Use Mixing (MMD)" and "Use Mixing (Tracker)". In bottom of window, set "Default Channel Mode" cycle to "Mixing". Also, setting the check for "Non-Planar Display" is something you should do if running on a graphics card. Exit.

So you don't have to go through the whole process again, save the settings. Now load up a module and give it a shot!
@endnode

@node Program
@title "About the program"
@{b}About The Maestrix@{ub}

This program was written using Amiga E, and should be compatible with any Kickstart from version 2 and up. When it runs, it will initialise itself and add it's own "maestix.library" to the system. From there you can use any programs that make use of the original. Please note, that to simplify things, it only supports playback and not recording as of this stage. A V39 compatible API of the maestix.library is implemented.

It requires AHI to be installed, of course, and a program that can make use of the library. Such as OctaMED SoundStudio.
@endnode

@node Trouble
@title Help!
@{b}Troubleshooting@{ub}

If you are having problems with the tooltypes have a look @{"here." link Instruct} Otherwise this section may help.

@{b}Q: @{ub}@{i}I'm using The Maestrix with SoundStudio, and everything is fine, until I switch screens and work with another task. Then the sound starts stuttering.@{ui}

@{b}A: @{ub}This is because the sound buffers being sent through AHI can loose sync when a load is put on the CPU, such as through disk access. I'm currently working a solution to this, but one thing you can do, is to trigger an action in SoundStudio to restart the music playing. I'd also recommend increasing the Mix Buffer, changing from the default 300, to a more sizeable 3000 would be a good start.
@endnode

@node Technical
@title "Technical details"
@{b}Technical details@{ub}

The Maestrix implements a version 39 API of the maestix.library, for playback only, just enough to use it as a conduit for AHI. The following is a list of supported functions:

AllocMaestro()
SetMaestro()
TransmitData()
FlushTransmit()
GetStatus()
FreeMaestro()

These have their limitations as well. SetMaestro() only sets frequency. GetStatus() will only return status and rate.

Unsupported functions (but included in library):

ReceiveData()
FlushReceive()
StartRealTime()
StopRealTime()

@{b}I already have a MaestroPro@{ub}

Then you don't need The Maestrix, as you already a full library to support your card. @{i}But I want to try it out with AHI.@{ui} This question might as well be @{i}What if I select my card as a MaestroPro in AHI which it really isn't?@{ui} Don't do this at home. No really, don't. Just to explain why you shouldn't, AHI and The Maestrix will most probably end up in a deadlock along with everything else attempting to use them. @{i}Why?@{ui} Okay, your sound program opens up AHI, which then loads up the AHI driver for the MaestroPro. This driver opens the maestix.library, uh oh, and calls the function to allocate the sound hardware. This will end up calling the function in my libray instead, which then will signal the master task to open AHI, AHI will then go through the same process again, this time however it will be waiting for my alloc function to come back because only one request is dealt with at a time and then everything trying to use AHI will end up waiting forever. But at least they shouldn't run out of stack!
@endnode

@node Author
@title "About the author"
@{b}About me@{ub}

Born in Australia, I first discovered programming in my early teens by reading Usborne computer books and got the bug from there. I'd written my first BASIC program before I even acquired an actual computer! However, soon after I became the new proud owner of a Commodore C16. And I got to test out my program, it worked! More to my delight was finding out about the machine code monitor built in contrast with the lack of instructions with it. That didn't stop my inquisitive mind and pretty soon I was disassembling code and printing out hex dumps on the MPS1250 dot matrix, learning 8-bit machine code and assembly language in the process. Much to the dismay of my Mother, who along with my friends thought I was weird. "Why can't you act normal like the other kids and just play games?", was one encouraging comment. I continued to code in assembler as well as BASIC writing all sorts of stuff, mostly games cheat hacking. Until I started experimenting externally as well and ended up short fusing my machine. A sad day of my life, my life was empty for time until I had to accept new technologies and my parents offer to replace it with a brand new Commodore-Amiga A500.

Soon after I learnt all over again, and not dissimilar to the first time, began programming in AmigaBASIC and yearning to learn 68k assembler. I did so, this time from Abacus books and convinced my Dad to fork out $200 or so dollars for a copy of AssemPro, and since I considered myself an advanced user, $750 for a harddisk.

I spent years doing this, and gained a vested interest in music, sampling and trackers. Apart from games which I also liked, if I wasn't in AssemPro I'd be ProTracking around! I'd soon outgrow the hardware and eventually upgraded to an A1200. The dream machine. Especially since it became my dream machine. I explored other languages, including the popularised C which I couldn't get into. Assembler was hard enough, but this language just confused me! Believe me, I know, I became an expert on it when I started converting C to assembler just to learn how it worked! I stuck with assembler until one came along which caught my eye. Amiga E. 

Although at first it just spewed out errors, I gave it a second chance and never looked back. From commands to programs with full GUI's. It was a big change from assembler. Allowing me to do more, especially with the up to date include files and soon would become my language of choice. Being able to include my own assembly was the icing on the cake, a perfect combination for me. I continued to do what I do best to this very day, more programming and less documenting. My worse programming habit!

I do tend to write essays in the finish, but I hope you enjoyed the story!
@endnode

