@node Why
@title "Why The Maestrix?"
@{b}Why The Maestrix?@{ub}

There has always been talk of writing a library that would emulate one written for a specific Amiga sound card but route it's output instead through AHI. Allowing the library to be used as a conduit for any soundcard with an AHI driver. The Toccata library has always been a popular choice, through the amount of traffic I have seen on group lists, suggesting this particular API as if no other existed. If we take SoundStudio as an example, it supports this, as well as Delfina. And of course Maestix. I downloaded the API documentation for these three API's, and examined each, to see what the possibility of writing an AHI based emulation of the library would be. Toccata looked possible, but also has a ot of functions, and it wasn't exactly clear to me which particular functions were needed for playback only. On the other hand, Delfina looked a lot more complex, as it didn't seem to have any standard functions for playing a sound stream but instead relied on some kind of interrupt mechanism. Then there is the Maestix. Not too many functions, and after a read through the autodoc, I decided that this had the most simple and straight forward way of playing samples with a minumum of fuss. All there was is functions to allocate, set parameters, play a sample buffer and clean up. So the choice was made, and I also came up with what I thought was a pretty snappy title, I just had to do the work and verify it as proof of concept. About that title, yeah once you know about it obvious, but just to explain: It "trix" the audio software into thinking it's using the Maestix, so they can work as usual, because behind the scenes there is The Maestrix.
@endnode